ViewState enables you to persist state information across page requests in
ASP.NET web forms. It is especially useful for retaining data during round-trip
events like button clicks and form submissions.


HOW VIEWSTATE WORKS

 * Locality: The ViewState property, present in the Page class, is scoped to
   specific instances of a web form and ensures that state data is kept related
   to that form only.

 * Persistence: The view state data, including its type, can be preserved across
   postback events either in the page or in a hidden input of the page.

 * Connection and Data Integrity: It relies on hidden fields and state
   information that is usually embedded in web forms. It ensures coordinated
   communication and synchronization between the server and different positioned
   form fields.

 * Obfuscation: The data in ViewState is encoded, but not encrypted, offering a
   level of security against tampering.

 * Round-Trip: This mechanism preserves state during a round trip from client to
   server and back, obviating the need to retrieve or recompute the data.


WHEN TO USE VIEWSTATE

 * Scope Management: To safeguard values within a form across postbacks without
   the need for requesting them from the client or the database.

 * Data Preservation: For maintaining control state even during validation or
   subsequent round-trip events.

 * Sensitivity: For storing non-sensitive data, as ViewState is client-side,
   readable, and modifiable.


SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS

 * Limited Sensitivity: While data is obfuscated, it's not encrypted and can be
   decoded. Therefore, avoid storing highly confidential or sensitive
   information.

 * Potential Attack Point: ViewState tampering is a known attack vector.
   Developers should closely monitor and validate data in the ViewState.


CODE EXAMPLE: VIEWSTATE

Here is the C# code:

  protected void Page_Load(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // On initial load, set a ViewState value
        if (!IsPostBack)
        {
            ViewState["Count"] = 0;
        }
    }

    protected void IncreaseCountButton_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Increment count in ViewState and display
        int count = (int)ViewState["Count"];
        count++;
        ViewState["Count"] = count;
        CountLabel.Text = "Count: " + count;

        // Other form elements are not affected
    }

User Controls and Custom Controls offer modularity and code reusability in
ASP.NET, but on different scales. While User Controls are confined to single web
forms, Custom Controls can be used broadly across the website.


USER CONTROLS

A User Control is like a mini web form that you can build separately and then
embed into your main web forms. This makes it ideal for creating standalone,
reusable components.

USE-CASES

 * Repeated sections in a website (headers, footers, sidebars).
 * Elements specific to a section of the website (like a product catalog).

ASPX & CODE-BEHIND

 * ASPX: A user control is generally composed of an .ascx file, which defines
   the control's structure and elements.
 * Code-Behind: For behaviors, you can have a separate code-behind file
   (.ascx.cs), or you can embed your code in the .ascx file itself.

CODE EXAMPLE: USER CONTROL

Here is the C# code:

// Sample UC: MyUserControl.ascx

<%@ Control Language="C#" AutoEventWireup="true" CodeBehind="MyUserControl.ascx.cs" Inherits="MyNamespace.MyUserControl" %>

<!-- UC elements go here. -->

// Sample UC Code-behind: MyUserControl.ascx.cs

public partial class MyUserControl : System.Web.UI.UserControl
{
    protected void Page_Load(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Logic here.
    }
}



CUSTOM CONTROLS

A Custom Control in ASP.NET is a more sophisticated type of control that you can
design and configure from scratch to suit your specific needs.

DESIGN & IMPLEMENTATION

Custom controls are more aligned with the look and feel of standard ASP.NET
server controls but are highly customizable.

 * HTML Output: You have total control of the HTML and can dynamically generate
   it.
 * Embedded Resources: You can package CSS, JavaScript, and images as part of
   your custom control.

TYPES OF CUSTOM CONTROLS

 * User-Created: These are controls you create by extending existing controls or
   building from scratch.
 * Composite Controls: They are composed of other controls or custom controls.
 * Rendered Content Controls: They render UI elements from code or a template.

REGISTERED VS UNREGISTERED

 * Unregistered: You can use these controls on a single page.
 * Registered: Once registered in the web.config or page, they can be used
   across the site.

CODE EXAMPLE: CUSTOM CONTROL

Here is the C# code:

// Sample CC: MyCustomControl.cs

using System;
using System.Web.UI;
using System.Web.UI.WebControls;

[assembly: TagPrefix("MyNamespace", "cc")]

namespace MyNamespace
{
    public class MyCustomControl : CompositeControl
    {
        private TextBox textBox;
        private Button button;

        protected override void CreateChildControls()
        {
            textBox = new TextBox();
            button = new Button();

            this.Controls.Add(textBox);
            this.Controls.Add(button);
        }

        protected override void Render(HtmlTextWriter writer)
        {
            textBox.RenderControl(writer);
            button.RenderControl(writer);
        }
    }
}

// Using the Custom Control in ASPX

<%@ Register Assembly="MyAssembly" Namespace="MyNamespace" TagPrefix="cc" %>
<cc:MyCustomControl runat="server" />

When it comes to validation, the best practice is to use a combination of
client-side (typically with JavaScript) and server-side (in C# or VB.NET)
techniques for robust security.


COMMON VALIDATION STRATEGIES

 * Client-Side: This ensures quick feedback to users without needing a server
   round-trip. However, it should be seen as a supplement to server-side
   validation, not a replacement.
 * Server-Side: This is the ultimate authority. Even if client-side validation
   passes, the server must always validate data to prevent attacks like SQL
   injection and Cross-Site Scripting (XSS).


TWO-STEP VALIDATION

 1. Client-Side JavaScript Validation: Enables instant feedback to users.

    // Example: Validate required fields
    if(document.getElementById('username').value === ''){
        alert('Username is required');
        return false;
    }


 2. Server-Side Validation in ASP.NET: A failsafe using the Page.IsValid
    property and Validator controls. ASP.NET also provides comprehensive
    validation controls like RegularExpressionValidator and
    RequiredFieldValidator.

    <asp:RequiredFieldValidator runat="server" 
    	ControlToValidate="txtUserName" 
    	ErrorMessage="Username is required." />

    if(Page.IsValid){
        // Process form
    }



BENEFITS OF A DUAL-VALIDATION APPROACH

 * Enhanced User Experience: Quick client-side feedback avoids unnecessary
   server requests.

 * Security and Server-Side Reliability: Crucial for sensitive operations.

 * Consistency and Flexibility: Even without JavaScript, server-side validation
   ensures data integrity.


CODE EXAMPLE: DUAL VALIDATION

Here is the updated ASP.NET code snippet with both client-side JavaScript and
server-side C#:

ASP.NET & JAVASCRIPT

<form id="form1" runat="server" onsubmit="return validateForm();">
    <input type="text" id="username" />
    <asp:Button ID="btnSubmit" runat="server" Text="Submit" OnClick="btnSubmit_Click" />
</form>

<script>
    function validateForm() {
        var username = document.getElementById('username').value;
        if (username.trim() === '') {
            alert('Username is required.');
            return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
</script>


C#

protected void btnSubmit_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(Request.Form["username"]))
    {
        // Proceed with form processing
    }
}

For setting up an ASP.NET application for database interaction, you would
generally use ADO.NET or Entity Framework.


ADO.NET

 * Components: ADO.NET utilizes Connection, Command, DataReader, DataAdapter,
   and DataSet.

 * Connection: Establishes the link to the database.

 * Command: Executes SQL statements, either SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE.

 * DataReader: Retrieves read-only and forward-only data, suitable when reading
   large datasets.

 * DataAdapter: Acts as a bridge between the database and DataSet. It enables
   data manipulation through the DataSet.

 * DataSet: In-memory representation of data, typically preferred in scenarios
   where data needs to be worked with offline before final updates to the
   database.

   Code Sample, C#:

   using (var connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
   {
       var command = new SqlCommand("SELECT * FROM Customers", connection);
       connection.Open();

       var dataReader = command.ExecuteReader();
       while (dataReader.Read())
       {
           Console.WriteLine($"{dataReader["Name"]}, {dataReader["Age"]}");
       }
   }



ENTITY FRAMEWORK

Entity Framework (EF) is an ORM that simplifies data access by mapping database
tables to C# classes.

 * DbContext: Acts as a bridge between the application and the database and
   represents a session with the database. It's often used in a using statement
   to manage the lifecycle of the connection and resources.

 * DbSet: Represents the table in the database and is used for querying and
   performing data manipulation operations.

 * LINQ: Provides a cleaner way to write queries, mainly using the Query Syntax
   or Method Syntax.

 * Code First and Model First: Let developers work either with C# classes and EF
   takes care of creating the database, or they can design the database first,
   and EF generates the C# classes.

 * Change Tracking: EF keeps track of any changes made to the objects, and when
   the changes are to be made in the database, it efficiently updates only the
   changed data.

   Code Sample, C#:

   using (var context = new MyDbContext())
   {
       var customers = context.Customers.Where(c => c.Age > 25);
       foreach (var customer in customers)
       {
           Console.WriteLine($"{customer.Name}, {customer.Age}");
       }
   }



KEY TAKEAWAYS

 1. Tradition Meets Modern: ADO.NET provides more granular control over database
    operations, while EF streamlines the process with the ORM model.

 2. Mind the Disconnect: Unlike ADO.NET, EF uses a 'context' that needs to be
    managed throughout the application.

Entity Framework (EF) forms an integral part of the ASP.NET technology stack,
contributing to data access and ORM (object-relational mapping).


CORE COMPONENTS

 * ObjectContext: Responsible for managing entity state, tracking changes, and
   error handling. However, it's more suitable for earlier versions of EF than
   for current applications.

 * DbContext: This newer and more commonly used component acts as a bridge
   between the app and the database, providing functions for database
   operations, such as find, add, or remove. It also ensures Change Tracking.


CODE-FIRST, MODEL-FIRST, AND DATABASE-FIRST WORKFLOWS

EF supports distinct workflows of developing a data model:

 * Code-First enables model and database creation based on C# classes.
 * Model-First facilitates visual design of the conceptual model, with database
   and classes following suit.
 * Database-First involves data model creation from an existing database.


QUERIES AND EAGER LOADING

EF employs LINQ to formulate queries against the data model. Additionally, it
allows for Eager Loading, ensuring related entities are readily available in
memory.


INTEGRATION WITH WEB APPLICATIONS

In web setups, two primary methods of employing EF are:

 * Database-First: Suitable for existing databases, this approach generates
   models from database schemas using the Entity Data Model Wizard.

 * Code-First Migrations: It's tailored for evolving databases, where developers
   create and alter the database schema as per application requirements.


BEST PRACTICES

 * Repository Pattern: segregates the data access logic and business logic.
 * Unit of Work: Bundles related operations, ensuring success or failure as an
   entirety.
 * Dependency Injection: Use an IoC container to configure EF, promoting
   cleaner, modular code.


SAMPLE CODE: CODE-FIRST WORKFLOW

Here is the Csharp code:

public class Product {
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public double Price { get; set; }
}

public class YourDbContext : DbContext {
    public DbSet<Product> Products { get; set; }

    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder) {
        modelBuilder.Entity<Product>().ToTable("tblProducts"); // Custom table name
    }
}

// Register DbContext in Startup.cs
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services) {
    services.AddDbContext<YourDbContext>(options =>
        options.UseSqlServer(Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection")));
}

// Usage in controller
public class ProductController : Controller {
    private readonly YourDbContext _context;

    public ProductController(YourDbContext context) {
        _context = context;
    }

    public IActionResult Create(Product product) {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        _context.SaveChanges();
    }
}

ASP.NET is a web framework while ADO.NET is a data management engine that serves
as ASP.NET's primary data access platform.


ADO.NET COMPONENTS

 1. Connection: Manages the link between the application and the database.
 2. Command: Executes queries and performs operations.
 3. DataReader: Streams a read-only, forward-only dataset.
 4. DataAdapter: Acts as a bridge between the dataset and the database,
    primarily used for data retrieval.
 5. DataSet: In-memory data cache that's disconnected from the database,
    enabling data manipulation before sending updates to the database.


USING ADO.NET IN ASP.NET

Both ASP.NET Web Forms and ASP.NET MVC support ADO.NET. Developers can choose
specific ADO.NET components based on requirements:

 * SqlConnection for establishing connections to SQL Server databases.
 * SqlCommand to execute SQL queries or stored procedures.
 * SqlDataReader to iterate through fetched data, suitable for read-only, fast
   data access.
 * SqlDataAdapter to fill and update data in a DataSet.
 * DataSet to disconnect and work with data in-memory before updating the
   database.
 * DataTable to represent data in a tabular form for the DataSet.


CODE EXAMPLE: USING ADO.NET IN ASP.NET

Here is the C# code:

using System;
using System.Data;
using System.Data.SqlClient;

public partial class Default : System.Web.UI.Page
{
    protected void Page_Load(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        if (!IsPostBack)
        {
            BindEmployeeData();
        }
    }

    protected void BindEmployeeData()
    {
        string connectionString = "Your Connection String";
        string query = "SELECT * FROM Employee";
        using (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
        {
            using (SqlDataAdapter adapter = new SqlDataAdapter(query, connection))
            {
                DataSet dataset = new DataSet();
                adapter.Fill(dataset, "Employee");
                if (dataset.Tables["Employee"].Rows.Count > 0)
                {
                    GridView1.DataSource = dataset;
                    GridView1.DataBind();
                }
            }
        }
    }

    protected void btnSave_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        string name = txtName.Text;
        int age = Convert.ToInt32(txtAge.Text);
        string connectionString = "Your Connection String";
        string query = "INSERT INTO Employee (Name, Age) VALUES (@Name, @Age)";
        using (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(connectionString))
        {
            using (SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand(query, connection))
            {
                command.Parameters.AddWithValue("@Name", name);
                command.Parameters.AddWithValue("@Age", age);
                connection.Open();
                command.ExecuteNonQuery();
                connection.Close();
            }
        }
        BindEmployeeData();
    }
}

Object-Relational Mapping (ORM) frameworks are tools that bridge the gap between
object-oriented software and relational databases. They execute this role via
three primary functions: data management, query translation, and data
synchronization.


DATA MANAGEMENT

ORM ensures coherent and error-free data interaction by managing:

 * State Tracking: Ensuring that changes to objects are reflected in the
   database.
 * Identity Tracking: Guaranteeing object uniqueness and avoiding duplicate
   records.
 * Data Validations: Implementing business rules for data consistency. This
   includes ensuring objects remain in a valid state.


QUERY TRANSLATION

ORM interprets object-oriented queries into SQL, optimizing and executing them
against the database. It handles:

 * Lazy Loading: Retrieving associated data only when needed, decreasing network
   traffic and enhancing performance.
 * Object-Relational Mappings: Defining how objects relate to database
   structures, consolidating complex operations. This merging can be done via
   Data Annotations, Fluent API, or through attributes.


DATA SYNCHRONIZATION

ORM ensures databases and application data are in sync by:

 * Unit of Work Pattern: Collecting atomic changes to the data, guaranteeing
   their consistency. It then processes these changes in a single transaction.
 * Object Identity Management: Keeping track of objects to ascertain any
   modifications, additions, or deletions. This method ensures accurate database
   representations without duplications or omissions.


CODE EXAMPLE: ORM IN ASP.NET CORE (ENTITY FRAMEWORK CORE)

Here is the C# code:

public interface IUnitOfWork
{
    IRepository<Book> Books { get; }
    IRepository<Author> Authors { get; }
    void SaveChanges();
}

public class UnitOfWork : IUnitOfWork
{
    private readonly MyDbContext _context;
    public UnitOfWork(MyDbContext context)
    {
        _context = context;
        Books = new Repository<Book>(context);
        Authors = new Repository<Author>(context);
    }

    public IRepository<Book> Books { get; private set; }
    public IRepository<Author> Authors { get; private set; }

    public void SaveChanges()
    {
        _context.SaveChanges();
    }
}

In ASP.NET MVC, you manage form submissions via HTML <form> elements.


ROUTES & CONTROLLERS

When a user submits a form, the browser sends a POST request to the server.
ASP.NET MVC processes this request using routes that are then mapped to specific
actions in controllers.

CODE EXAMPLE: ROUTES AND CONTROLLER ACTIONS

Here is the C# code:

public class HomeController : Controller
{
    [HttpGet]
    public IActionResult Index()
    {
        return View();
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult SubmitForm(UserModel model)
    {
        // Process the form data, possibly saving to a database
        return RedirectToAction("Success");
    }

    public IActionResult Success()
    {
        return View("Success");
    }
}



HANDLE FORM VALIDATION

You can validate form data before the controller action is triggered.

CODE EXAMPLE: HANDLING VALIDATION

Here is the C# code:

[HttpPost]
public IActionResult SubmitForm(UserModel model)
{
    if (!ModelState.IsValid)
    {
        return View(model);
    }
    // Process the form data
    return RedirectToAction("Success");
}


In the example above, if the UserModel does not pass validation, the method
returns the same view with validation errors.


SEND FEEDBACK TO THE USER

You can use various methods to provide feedback to the user after form
submission.

CODE EXAMPLE: FEEDBACK TO THE USER

Here is the C# code:

[HttpPost]
public IActionResult SubmitForm(UserModel model)
{
    if (!ModelState.IsValid)
    {
        // Return the view with validation errors
        return View(model);
    }

    // Process the form data and show a success message
    TempData["SuccessMessage"] = "Form submitted successfully!";
    return RedirectToAction("Success"); 
}

public IActionResult Success()
{
    ViewBag.Message = TempData["SuccessMessage"] ?? "";
    return View("Success");
}


In this example, after a successful form submission, a success message is stored
in TempData and then retrieved and displayed on the 'Success' view.

Razor is an intuitive and productive server-side view engine utilized in
ASP.NET, especially for ASP.NET MVC.

It combines HTML and C# or VB.NET in a clean and straightforward syntax. The
ParseTemple method parses Razor template code. It uses a templating engine to
render dynamic content.


KEY FEATURES

 * Inline C# and VB.NET code: Eases embedding server-side logic into dynamic web
   pages.
 * Code Blocks: Defines C# or VB.NET methods for executing during rendering.
 * Expression Blocks: Evaluates and outputs a single C# or VB.NET expression or
   statement.
 * Layouts: Allows for defining parent templates that structure content across
   multiple views.
 * Model Data: Provides strongly-typed model data for views, enhancing code
   readability and simplifying common tasks like form validation.
 * Helpers: Centralizes frequently used HTML components or rendering logic for
   easier reuse.


VARIANTS

 * Razor Pages: Offers a page-focused approach, especially for simpler web
   applications.


RAZOR SYNTAX: CODE EXAMPLES

CODE BLOCK

The following example employs a @{ } code block to calculate a time delay before
triggering a Redirect:

C#:

@model Person
@{
    if (!User.IsAuthenticated) 
    { 
        var url = "/login?returnUrl=" + Request.Url;
        Response.Redirect(url);
    }
}


EXPRESSIONS

Razor enables embedded C# or VB.NET expressions using the @ symbol.

Example:

<p>
    Welcome, <strong>@User.GetName()</strong>!
</p>


CODE STATEMENTS

For multi-line server-side statements, use @{ } code blocks:

<div>
    @{ 
        var customerCount = ViewBag.CustomerCount;
        var message = customerCount == 1 ? "There is 1 customer." : $"There are {customerCount} customers.";
        <p>@message</p>
    }
</div>


MODEL DATA BINDING

Ensure distinct views correspond to specific models for type-safety.

For instance, in a Controller:

public IActionResult Edit(int? id) 
{
    if (id == null) return NotFound();
    var person = PersonRepo.Get(id.Value);
    if (person == null) return NotFound();
    return View(person);
}


Then in the corresponding View:

@model Person
@{
    ViewBag.Title = "Edit";
}
...



ADVANTAGES

 * Intellisense and Validation Support: Capable editors provide Code-completion
   suggestions and check for syntax errors.
 * Compilation Efficiency: Razor templates are compiled, enhancing performance
   and validating correctness before deployment.
 * Consistency and Maintainability: Well-designed templates promote clear,
   consistent view structures that are easier to modify and troubleshoot.


EMPIRICAL PERFORMANCE

In 2019, a TechEmpower benchmark noted that Razor achieved greater throughput
than its four principal competitors: Handlebars, Velocity, JSP, and Smarty,
although it narrowly trailed Jade.

Routing in ASP.NET enables configuring URL routes for web applications, making
URLs more readable and search engine-friendly.


KEY COMPONENTS

 1. Route Table: A collection of defined routes.
 2. Route Handler: Directs matching routes to appropriate resources.
 3. Route Collection: Associated with the current HttpContext, it manages
    routing for the request.


ROLE OF ROUTING WITHIN ASP.NET

 * Requests and Mapping: Translates route URLs into the corresponding request
   actions.
 * Reverse Mapping: Enables the generation of URLs from route definitions.
 * Decoupling: Allows for loosely coupled navigation between URLs and resources.


IMPLEMENTING ROUTING IN ASP.NET

GLOBAL.ASAX.CS

The Application_Start method provides a central place to define routes using
RouteTable.Routes.

using System.Web.Routing;

public class Global : HttpApplication {
    protected void Application_Start(object sender, EventArgs e) {
        RouteTable.Routes.MapPageRoute("RouteAlias", "myUrl", "~/Target.aspx");
    }
}


WEBFORMS

In the destination .aspx file, form elements like HyperLink can reference
routes. The code below binds a route to a hyperlink named myLink:

<asp:HyperLink ID="myLink" runat="server" NavigateUrl="<%$ RouteUrl:RouteAlias %>" />


MVC

In MVC, a RouteConfig class in the App_Start folder defines routes. Here's an
example with a more nuanced route using MVC Attribute Routing:

using System.Web.Mvc;
using System.Web.Routing;

public class RouteConfig {
    public static void RegisterRoutes(RouteCollection routes) {
        routes.IgnoreRoute("{resource}.axd/{*pathInfo}");
        routes.MapMvcAttributeRoutes();
    }
}



ENHANCED ROUTING TECHNIQUES

 * Constraint-based Routing: Apply conditions to routes based on URL parts.
 * Constraints: Ensure a route is only matched under certain conditions.
 * RegularExpression Constraints: Employ RegEx patterns for more precise route
   matches.

EXAMPLE: ADDING A REGEX CONSTRAINT

In this case, the id URL parameter should be numerical:

public static void RegisterRoutes(RouteCollection routes) {
    routes.IgnoreRoute("{resource}.axd/{*pathInfo}");
    routes.MapRoute(
        name: "CustomerId",
        url: "home/customer/{id}",
        defaults: new { controller = "Home", action = "CustomerInfo", id=UrlParameter.Optional },
        constraints: new { id = @"\d+" }
    );
}

In ASP.NET, you define routes using MVC Route attributes and the RouteConfig
file.


CODE EXAMPLE: ROUTE CONFIGURATIONS

Here is the RouteConfig.cs for the MVC Application:

public class RouteConfig
{
    public static void RegisterRoutes(RouteCollection routes)
    {
        routes.IgnoreRoute("{resource}.axd/{*pathInfo}");

        routes.MapRoute(
           name: "Default",
           url: "{controller}/{action}/{id}",
           defaults: new { controller = "Home", action = "Index", id = UrlParameter.Optional }
        );
    }
}



IMPORTANCE OF ROUTES

Routes direct web requests to the correct controller action within an MVC
application. Each route contains a combination of controller, action, and
optional parameters, minimizing binding and processing efforts.

ASP.NET MVC uses route constraints to ensure that routes are matched only under
specific conditions. This is achieved through route data, which contains values
for keys like controller, action, and any other route values.


ROUTE DATA AND CONSTRAINTS

ASP.NET MVC routes use data provided by the IRouteConstraint interface. You can
inherit this interface to create custom constraints as needed.

The route's constraints property can be set as shown below:

routes.MapRoute(
    name: "Default",
    url: "{controller}/{action}/{id}",
    defaults: new { controller = "Home", action = "Index", id = UrlParameter.Optional },
    constraints: new { id = @"\d+" }  // ID must be a number
);


> Use existing constraints like min, max, minlength, maxlength, or create custom
> ones.


CODE EXAMPLE: BASIC CONSTRAINTS

Here is the C# code:

public static void RegisterRoutes(RouteCollection routes)
{
    routes.IgnoreRoute("{resource}.axd/{*pathInfo}");

    routes.MapRoute(
        name: "Default",
        url: "{controller}/{action}/{id}",
        defaults: new { controller = "Home", action = "Index", id = UrlParameter.Optional },
        constraints: new { id = @"\d+" }  // ID must be a number
    );
}



CODE EXAMPLE: CUSTOM CONSTRAINT

Here is the C# code:

public class AlphaRouteConstraint : IRouteConstraint
{
    public AlphaRouteConstraint() { }

    public bool Match(HttpContextBase httpContext, Route route, string parameterName, RouteValueDictionary values, RouteDirection routeDirection)
    {
        object value;
        if (values.TryGetValue(parameterName, out value) && value != null)
        {
            return Regex.IsMatch(value.ToString(), @"^[a-zA-Z]+$");
        }

        return false;
    }
}

public static void RegisterRoutes(RouteCollection routes)
{
    routes.IgnoreRoute("{resource}.axd/{*pathInfo}");

    routes.MapRoute(
        name: "AlphaOnly",
        url: "alpha/{id}",
        defaults: new { controller = "Alpha", action = "Index", id = UrlParameter.Optional },
        constraints: new { id = new AlphaRouteConstraint() }  // ID must contain only letters
    );

    // ... other routes
}


Simply put, route constraints are rules defined within routes to guide or
restrict the matching process for incoming URLs. Whether you're implementing
standard constraints, like requiring a datetime format, or designing custom
constraints specific to your application, ASP.NET's routing system offers
flexibility and control.

Web APIs need robust security to protect sensitive data and applications.
Securing them begins with authentication, using methods like tokens,
certificates, and API keys, and is continued through authorization and API
management.


COMMON SECURITY APPROACHES FOR WEB APIS

 1. Pass-Through Authentication: Let the client's credentials directly access
    the backend services. It's simple but less secure.

 2. Basic Authentication: Clients send a Base64-encoded username and password
    with each request. It's simple to implement but has security risks.

 3. API Keys: A unique identifier is issued to clients for interacting with the
    API. While simple, it's crucial to keep API keys secure.

 4. Bearer Tokens: Upon successful login or API key validation, the server
    issues a time-bound token that clients include with subsequent requests.
    It's time-bound and can be revoked.

 5. OAuth: For secure, reliable, and regulated access, platforms like AWS
    provide OAuth 2.0-based authentication.

 6. JSON Web Tokens (JWT): A self-contained token with defined claims that can
    serve as the credential for token-based systems.


ADDITIONAL LAYER OF AUTHORIZATION

Even after successful authentication, API requests must be authorized based on
the user's role or specific attributes. This can be achieved using role-based or
attribute-based authorization rules.


API MANAGEMENT

Centralized control over API access and monitoring is achieved. This involves
setting access limitssuch as requests per secondunderstanding usage patterns,
and ensuring security through threat prevention methods like DDoS attack
mitigation and data encryption.


CODE EXAMPLE: JWT VERIFICATION MIDDLEWARE IN ASP.NET

Here is the C# code:

// Startup.cs
using Microsoft.Extensions.Configuration;
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer;
using System.Text;

public class Startup
{
    public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
    {
        var key = Encoding.ASCII.GetBytes(Configuration["Jwt:Key"]);
        services.AddAuthentication(JwtBearerDefaults.AuthenticationScheme)
                  .AddJwtBearer(options =>
                  {
                      options.TokenValidationParameters = new TokenValidationParameters
                      {
                          ValidateIssuer = true,
                          ValidateAudience = true,
                          ValidateLifetime = true,
                          ValidateIssuerSigningKey = true,
                          ValidIssuer = Configuration["Jwt:Issuer"],
                          ValidAudience = Configuration["Jwt:Issuer"],
                          IssuerSigningKey = new SymmetricSecurityKey(key)
                      };
                  });
    }

    public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
    {
         app.UseAuthentication();
         app.UseAuthorization();
    }
}

In Asp.Net Core, you can handle different HTTP verbs by decorating methods with
appropriate attributes. These attributes help map HTTP requests to specific
methods.


KEY ATTRIBUTES FOR HTTP VERBS

 * [HttpGet]: Matches a GET request.
 * [HttpPost]: Matches a POST request.
 * [HttpPut]: Matches a PUT request.
 * [HttpDelete]: Matches a DELETE request.
 * [Route("{name}")]: Specifies a unique route for the method.


SAMPLE CODE: HTTP VERB HANDLING

Here is the C# code:

[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class ItemController : ControllerBase
{
    private readonly List<Item> _items = new List<Item>();

    [HttpGet]
    public ActionResult<List<Item>> GetItems()
    {
        return _items;
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult CreateItem(Item item)
    {
        _items.Add(item);
        return CreatedAtAction(nameof(GetItems), new { id = item.Id }, item);
    }

    [HttpPut("{id}")]
    public IActionResult UpdateItem(int id, Item updatedItem)
    {
        var existingItem = _items.FirstOrDefault(i => i.Id == id);
        if (existingItem == null) return NotFound();

        existingItem.Name = updatedItem.Name;
        existingItem.Description = updatedItem.Description;

        return NoContent();
    }

    [HttpDelete("{id}")]
    public IActionResult DeleteItem(int id)
    {
        var existingItem = _items.FirstOrDefault(i => i.Id == id);
        if (existingItem == null) return NotFound();

        _items.Remove(existingItem);

        return NoContent();
    }
}

