REST (Representational State Transfer) is a design approach for building
networked applications, especially web services. A RESTful system is
characterized by its adherence to a set of architectural principles that promote
loose coupling, scalability, and standardized communication patterns through
HTTP.

ASP.NET Web API provides a robust framework for creating RESTful web services.


KEY REST PRINCIPLES

 * Stateless Communication: Each request from the client to the server must
   contain all the information necessary to understand and process the request.
   The server doesn't store any client context between requests, which helps to
   facilitate a clear division of client and server responsibilities and
   enhances overall reliability.

 * Resource Identification: Resources, such as documents or images, are uniquely
   identifiable through URIs (Uniform Resource Identifiers). This clear and
   standardized method of identification is fundamental to REST's design
   approach and facilitates uniform access of system data.

 * Manipulation via Representations: The client has control and visibility of
   the resources, but the server manages the resources. A resource's state can
   be transferred from server to client, or vice versa, in the form of
   representations (commonly in the JSON or XML format).

 * Self-Describing Messages: Each message between a client and server contains
   all the information necessary to correctly process and interpret the data,
   aiding in system interoperability.


HOW ASP.NET WEB API SUPPORTS REST

 1. HTTP-Centric URL Routing: Web API employs attribute-based routing or
    convention-based routing to direct HTTP requests to appropriate controller
    methods.

 2. MIME Message Formats: Web API supports content negotiation to select the
    most suitable representation when dealing with resource data. MIME
    (Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions) types help specify the type of data
    being sent.

 3. Stateless Communication: Web API inherently follows stateless communication.
    Each HTTP request from the client to the server encapsulates all the
    necessary information for the server to understand and process the request.

 4. HTTP Methods and Their Semantics: Web API aligns HTTP methods (GET, POST,
    PUT, DELETE, amongst others) with specific data-operations. For example, a
    DELETE request is associated with the operation of removing a resource.

 5. HTTP Response Codes: Web API leverages HTTP status codes to provide clear
    feedback to clients about the outcome of their requests. For instance, a 201
    status code might be used to signal successful resource creation.

 6. Data Representation via Content Negotiation: Web API caters to a range of
    client preferences through content negotiation. Clients can specify their
    preferred representation (like JSON or XML), which the server accommodates
    to the best of its capabilities.

 7. A Toolkit for Client-Server Communication: Web API equips you with the means
    to facilitate communication between client and server entities, enabling
    diverse client types (web browsers, mobile apps) to interact with server
    resources.

 8. Self-Description of Services: ASP.NET Web API supports the concept of having
    routes and methods that are discoverable. By providing consistent URIs and
    method semantics, the API can be self-descriptive.


CODE EXAMPLE: WEB API CONTROLLER FOR PRODUCTS

Here is the C sharp code:

using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Web.Http;

public class ProductsController : ApiController
{
    private static List<Product> products = new List<Product>
    {
        new Product { Id = 1, Name = "Product 1", Price = 99.99m },
        new Product { Id = 2, Name = "Product 2", Price = 149.99m },
    };

    public IEnumerable<Product> Get()
    {
        return products;
    }

    public IHttpActionResult Get(int id)
    {
        var product = products.FirstOrDefault(p => p.Id == id);
        if (product == null)
        {
            return NotFound();
        }
        return Ok(product);
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IHttpActionResult Post(Product product)
    {
        product.Id = products.Max(p => p.Id) + 1;
        products.Add(product);
        return CreatedAtRoute("DefaultApi", new { id = product.Id }, product);
    }

    [HttpPut]
    public IHttpActionResult Put(int id, Product product)
    {
        var existingProduct = products.FirstOrDefault(p => p.Id == id);
        if (existingProduct == null)
        {
            return NotFound();
        }
        existingProduct.Name = product.Name;
        existingProduct.Price = product.Price;
        return Ok();
    }

    [HttpDelete]
    public IHttpActionResult Delete(int id)
    {
        var product = products.FirstOrDefault(p => p.Id == id);
        if (product == null)
        {
            return NotFound();
        }
        products.Remove(product);
        return Ok();
    }
}

public class Product
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public decimal Price { get; set; }
}

In the context of ASP.NET, authentication validates a user's identity, while
authorization determines the actions they're allowed to perform. The system
works well with third-party OAuth providers and LDAP.


ASP.NET AUTHENTICATION

ASP.NET offers several authentication techniques:

 * Windows Authentication: Utilizes the Windows account for validation.
 * Forms Authentication: Validates users through a web form and maintains a
   cookie to identify them in subsequent requests.
 * Certificate Authentication: Requires users to present a digital certificate.


ASP.NET AUTHORIZATION

Authorization in ASP.NET allows or denies user actions. Defined at both
application and directory levels, it involves roles and user requirements.

 * Role-Based Authorization: Restricts access based on roles, ensuring, for
   example, that only administrators can access certain functions.
 * User-Based Authorization: Determines permissions based on individual user
   identities.
 * URL Authorization: Controls access to specific URLs or file types.
 * Claims-Based Authorization: Uses claims to make decisions, providing greater
   flexibility than just roles.


CODE EXAMPLE: IMPLEMENTING AUTHORIZATION IN ASP.NET

Here is the C# code:

using System.Web;
using System.Web.Security;

public class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : System.Web.Mvc.AuthorizeAttribute
{
    public string UserClaimType { get; set; }
    public string RoleClaimType { get; set; }

    protected override bool AuthorizeCore(HttpContextBase httpContext)
    {
        if (httpContext == null)
            throw new ArgumentNullException("httpContext");

        // Check for specific role claim
        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(RoleClaimType))
        {
            var claim = ((ClaimsPrincipal)httpContext.User).FindFirst(RoleClaimType);
            if (claim != null && Roles.Contains(claim.Value))
                return true;
        }

        // Check for specific user claim
        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(UserClaimType))
        {
            var claim = ((ClaimsPrincipal)httpContext.User).FindFirst(UserClaimType);
            if (claim != null && Users.Contains(claim.Value))
                return true;
        }

        return base.AuthorizeCore(httpContext);
    }

    protected override void HandleUnauthorizedRequest(AuthorizationContext filterContext)
    {
        var request = filterContext.HttpContext.Request;
        var response = filterContext.HttpContext.Response;

        if (request.IsAjaxRequest())
        {
            response.StatusCode = 403;
            response.StatusDescription = "You are not authorized for this action.";
            filterContext.Result = new JsonResult { Data = new { StatusCode = response.StatusCode, StatusDescription = response.StatusDescription }, JsonRequestBehavior = JsonRequestBehavior.DenyGet };
        }
        else
        {
            response.RedirectLocation = "~/Error/Unauthorized";
            response.Redirect();
        }
    }
}

