An ASP.NET web application, much like any software project, can be compiled in
different configurations. Two standard configurations are 'Debug' and 'Release'.


KEY DIFFERENCES

 * Optimization and Efficiency: A 'Release' build is optimized for performance,
   whereas a 'Debug' build sacrifices performance for better debugging
   capabilities. This optimization includes features like function inlining,
   which aren't present in 'Debug' builds.

 * Debugging Information: 'Release' builds strip out debug information to
   improve performance, while 'Debug' builds retain this information, making
   them larger but more suited for debugging.

 * Error and Exception Handling: 'Debug' builds are more lenient in generating
   unoptimized code paths to make the debugging process more straightforward. In
   contrast, 'Release' builds focus on robust performance, potentially leading
   to exceptions if errors are encountered.


CODE COMPARISON

Here is the C# code:

DEBUG BUILD

public void ExampleMethod()
{
    int x = 10;
    int y = 0;
    int z = x / y;  // This division will trigger an exception
}


RELEASE BUILD

public void ExampleMethod()
{
    int x = 10;
    int y = 0;
    int z = x / y;  // This division will not trigger an immediate exception in a Release build, making it a potential point of failure
}

The ASP.NET Core application uses a flexible configuration system that allows
you to retrieve key-value pairs from various data sources.


DATA SOURCES

The configuration system can retrieve settings from the following sources:

 * Built-in Configuration Providers: These include appsettings.json, user
   secrets, environment variables, command-line arguments, and in-memory data.

 * Configuration Providers: Additional providers such as Azure Key Vault, custom
   JSON files or databases may be used by calling Add method to include specific
   providers.


RETRIEVING CONFIGURATION SETTINGS

To access these settings, inject an IConfiguration interface into a component
and use its methods.

METHOD OVERVIEW

 * GetSection: Used to retrieve a nested set of configurations based on a
   specific key.
 * GetValue: Directly retrieves the value of a specific configuration key.
 * Bind: Binds a configuration section to an object or object graph.
 * Example: configuration.GetSection("Logging").


CONFIGURATION OPTIONS PATTERN

This pattern lets you use strongly-typed classes in your ASP.NET Core
application.

DEFINE A CONFIGURATION SECTION CLASS

Create a POCO for each configuration section you want to define.

Here is an example:

public class DatabaseConfig
{
    public string Server { get; set; }
    public string Port { get; set; }
    public string Username { get; set; }
    public string Password { get; set; }
}


REGISTER THE CONFIGURATION CLASS

In Startup.cs, use the ConfigureServices method to bind the settings class to
the configuration data:

public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services, IConfiguration configuration)
{
    services.Configure<DatabaseConfig>(configuration.GetSection("Database"));
}


INJECT THE CONFIGURATION CLASS

Use dependency injection to access the configuration in your application
components:

public class DatabaseService
{
    private readonly DatabaseConfig _config;

    public DatabaseService(IOptions<DatabaseConfig> config)
    {
        _config = config.Value;
    }

    public string GetConnectionString()
    {
        return $"Server={_config.Server};Port={_config.Port};User={_config.Username};Password={_config.Password}";
    }
}



AVOIDING HARD-CODED VALUES

The IOptions and IConfiguration interfaces enable you to inject configuration
settings into your components or services, reducing code coupling.


KEY POINTS

 * The configuration system in ASP.NET Core enables you to retrieve key-value
   pairs from various data sources, including both built-in and custom
   providers.
 * Use IConfiguration to retrieve values or sections directly, or use the
   configuration options pattern for strongly-typed settings.
 * Taking advantage of the options pattern decouples the configuration object
   from components.

Error handling in ASP.NET Core typically involves managing exceptions and
presenting user-friendly error messages.


MIDDLEWARE APPROACH

ASP.NET Core recommends using middleware for error handling. The
UseExceptionHandler method in Startup.Configure provides a centralized way to
capture exceptions.

Here's the middleware setup:

public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IHostingEnvironment env)
{
    if (env.IsDevelopment())
    {
        app.UseDeveloperExceptionPage();
    }
    else
    {
        app.UseExceptionHandler("/Home/Error");
        app.UseHsts();  // Secure the response with HSTS.
    }

    app.UseHttpsRedirection();
    app.UseStaticFiles();
    app.UseCookiePolicy();

    app.UseMvc(routes =>
    {
        routes.MapRoute(
            name: "default",
            template: "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");
    });
}



TYPES OF EXCEPTION HANDLING

 1. Developer Exception Page:

    * Enabled in the development environment by default.
    * Provides detailed error information and stack trace.

 2. Custom Error Page:

    * Configured with UseExceptionHandler.
    * Best for production; presents a user-friendly error page.

 3. Status Code Pages:

    * An alternative for custom error pages.
    * Intercepts specific status codes like 404 and presents an error page.


IMPLEMENTING A CUSTOM ERROR CONTROLLER

CODE

public class HomeController : Controller
{
    [Route("/Home/Error")]
    public IActionResult Error()
    {
        var exceptionHandlerPathFeature =
            HttpContext.Features.Get<IExceptionHandlerPathFeature>();

        ViewData["StatusCode"] = HttpContext.Response.StatusCode;
        ViewData["ExceptionMessage"] = exceptionHandlerPathFeature?.Error.Message;

        return View("Error");
    }
}


VIEW (ERROR.CSHTML)

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Error</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Error</h1>
    <p>Status Code: @ViewData["StatusCode"]</p>
    <p>Message: @ViewData["ExceptionMessage"]</p>
</body>
</html>


The UseExceptionHandler middleware redirects unhandled exceptions to the Error
action method within the Home controller.


HANDLING KNOWN EXCEPTIONS

It's crucial to differentiate between different types of exceptions, such as:

 * Application Exceptions: For expected issues like validation errors.
 * Infrastructure Exceptions: For server or database-related errors that need
   logging and monitoring.

For structured exception handling, consider using:

 * ProblemDetails Middleware: Flow standard HTTP error objects.
 * Action Filters: Can be used both globally and locally to handle exceptions
   before or after a view produces a response.


LOGGING WITH ILOGGER

ASP.NET Core provides ILogger for streamlined logging.

CODE

private readonly ILogger<HomeController> _logger;

public HomeController(ILogger<HomeController> logger)
{
    _logger = logger;
}

[Route("/Home/Error")]
public IActionResult Error()
{
    var exceptionHandlerPathFeature = 
        HttpContext.Features.Get<IExceptionHandlerPathFeature>();

    _logger.LogError($"The path {exceptionHandlerPathFeature.Path} " +
                     $"threw an exception: {exceptionHandlerPathFeature.Error}");

    ViewData["StatusCode"] = HttpContext.Response.StatusCode;
    ViewData["ExceptionMessage"] = exceptionHandlerPathFeature?.Error.Message;

    return View("Error");
