In ASP.NET, HTTP Handlers and HTTP Modules are powerful components that provide
fine-grained control over web request processing.


KEY DISTINCTIONS

 * HTTP Handler: Responsible for processing specific file types or URLs.
 * HTTP Module: Capable of intercepting and modifying any aspect of a web
   request.


CORE CONCEPTS

Both Handlers and Modules interface with the pipeline that directs how an
incoming HTTP request is processed. ASP.NET Core uses a middleware approach
similar to HTTP modules.

HTTP PIPELINE IN CLASSIC ASP.NET VS. ASP.NET CORE

Here's a comparison of classic ASP.NET and ASP.NET Core's request pipeline
handling:

[https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/dev-stack-app.appspot.com/o/http-handlers%2Fhttp-handlers-vs-middleware.webp?alt=media&token=699f7e96-d6a9-4e53-99a2-0073a0acca10]

 * HTTP Handler: In classic ASP.NET, it's executed first and can bypass other
   handlers. In ASP.NET Core, the equivalent middleware would run through
   sequentially unless it short-circuits.

 * HTTP Module: In classic ASP.NET, it can be configured to execute at specific
   pipeline stages, ranging from BeginRequest to Dispose. In ASP.NET Core,
   middleware runs through in a defined sequence.


CODE EXAMPLE: ASP.NET CORE MIDDLEWARE

Here is the C Sharp code:

ASP.NET CORE MIDDLEWARE


// ExampleMiddleware.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class ExampleMiddleware
{
    private readonly RequestDelegate _next;

    public ExampleMiddleware(RequestDelegate next)
    {
        _next = next;
    }

    public async Task InvokeAsync(HttpContext context)
    {
        // Before the request is processed
        await _next(context); // Ensure the request passes to the next middleware in sequence
        // After the request is processed
    }
}

// Startup.cs
public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app)
{
    app.UseMiddleware<ExampleMiddleware>();
}



